Titanic EDA¶

The goal of this EDA is to determine what features are likely to have contributed to Titanic passenger's survival.

2. Exploration and Data cleaning¶

Survived is Target/Dependent Variable - Following analysis is to understand the effect of other variable(s) on Survived variable.

  • PassengerId(numerical) - Unique Id assigned to each passenger
  • Survived(categorical) - 0 = No, 1 = Yes.
  • Pclass(categorical) - Passenger Class - 1, 2, 3
  • Name(object) - Passenger Name
  • Sex(categorical) - Passenger Sex
  • Age(numerical) - Passenger Age
  • SibSp(categorical) - Number of Siblings/Spouses on board
  • Parch(categorical) - Number of Parents/Children on board
  • Ticket(object) - Ticket number
  • Fare(numerical) - Ticket price
  • Cabin(object) - Cabin number
  • Embarked(categorical) - Stations from where a Passenger embarked from
    C - Cherbourg S - Southhampton Q - Queenstown

3.1 Univariate Analysis Observations¶

Categorical Data Observations¶
  1. Survived(Cat.) - Out of 891 passengers, only 38% survived which is 342. More than half(61.6%) the Passengers died. Number of passengers that did not survive is 549.
  2. PClass(Cat.) - Most passengers were in Pclass 3. More passengers travelled in Pclass 1 than in 2.
  3. Sex(Cat.) - There are more Males passengers than Female passengers
  4. SibSp(Cat.) - There are more single people traveling than in families. The SibSp and Parch are pointing to a family size which will be analyzed further.
  5. Parch(Cat.) - There are more single people traveling than in families. The SibSp and Parch are pointing to a family size which will be analyzed further.
  6. Embarked(Cat.) - There are more passengers that embarked from Southhampton as compared to Cherbourg or Queenstown
Numerical Data Observations¶
  1. Age(Num.) - Most passengers are in the age group between 20 - 40. Almost normally distributed. There are a few outliers.
  2. Fare(Num.) - Not normally distributed, highly skewed. Most passengers are paying less compared to few passengers that have paid a high price. Data is right skewed. There are a lot of outliers. There are passenger(s) that have paid more than $500. A family is assigned same ticket and the fare is same. Fare will need to be calculated per person instead of by family size as determined by SibSp and Parch values.
Mixed Data Obervations¶
  1. Name - Name column contains Passenger's surname, title and first name. This needs to be analyzed further.
  2. Ticket - Ticket number is same for the family members.

    a. Surname of passengers with the same ticket number is same and it should be mostly same.
    b. The Fare price is also same for all passengers and this would need to be analyzed further.
    c. The SibSp and Parch are pointing to a family size which will need to be analyzed further.

  3. Cabin - There are 77% missing values in this column.

Observations so far
Last name of Passengers with ticket 347082 are a family with last name = "Andersson" and a family_size of 7.

  1. A new column called family_size will be created which is made up of SibSp, Parch plus one (one for the person who is buying the ticket). family_size=SibSp+Parch+1
  2. A new column called family_type will be created which will show the family type(alone(1), small(2-4), large (>5)). This will help with future predictions of Survived variable
In [22]:
df['family_size'] = df['SibSp'].astype(int) + df['Parch'].astype(int) + 1
In [23]:
# family_type
# 1 -> alone
# 2-4 -> small
# >5 -> large

def transform_family_size(num):

  if num == 1:
    return 'alone'
  elif num>1 and num <5:
    return "small"
  else:
    return "large"
In [24]:
df['family_type'] = df['family_size'].apply(transform_family_size)

def fill_missing_age(row):
    pclass = row['Pclass']
    mean_age_pclass = df.query('Pclass==@pclass')['Age'].mean()    
    if pd.isnull(row['Age']):        
        return mean_age_pclass
    else:
        return row['Age']

df['Age'] = df.apply(fill_missing_age, axis=1)

# Function to add annotations
def add_annotations(crosstab, ax):
    for i, row in enumerate(crosstab.index):
        for j, col in enumerate(crosstab.columns):
            value = crosstab.iloc[i, j]
            ax.text(j + 0.5, i + 0.5, f'{value}', ha='center', va='center',
                    fontsize=14, color='white', weight='bold')
            
crosstab1 = pd.crosstab(df['Survived'], df['Pclass'], normalize='columns').round(2)
crosstab2 = pd.crosstab(df['Survived'], df['Embarked'], normalize='columns').round(1) 
crosstab3 = pd.crosstab(df['Survived'], df['Sex'],normalize='columns').round(2)
crosstab4 = pd.crosstab(df['Survived'], df['family_type'],normalize='columns').round(1)

            linewidths=0.5, linecolor='black')

sns.heatmap(crosstab4, annot=False, cmap='coolwarm', ax=axes[1,1], cbar=True,\
            linewidths=0.5, linecolor='black')

# Manually add annotations to ensure visibility

4.1.1 Observations - Categorical vs Categorical¶

  1. Pclass - Passengers in Pclass 1 have the highest survival rate(63%). Passengers in Pclass 3 had the most deaths(76%).
  2. Sex - Females(74%) survived more than Males.
  3. Embarked - Passengers that embarked from Chergourg(55%) had better survival rate compared to the passengers from Southhampton(34%) and Queenstown(39%).
  4. Family_type - Passengers belonging to small(58%) family_type survived the most. Supporting the assumption that families with small children were given priority and rescued first. Passengers belonging to Single(30%) and Large(20%) family_type had the lowest survival rate. This is an interesting observation - Mid size families had higher survival chance.
  5. Title - Passengers with titles - Master, Miss, Mlle, Mme, Mrs, Ms and the survived the most, further supporting the Sex criteria above. Titles such as Mr, Officer who were mostly males did not survive.

Assumptions 1 - Based on these 3 observations, following assumptions came up

  1. Passengers that embarked from Cherbourg had more female passengers or they had more number of Pclass passengers.
  2. Since Pclass 1 passengers survived the most, and also most Cherbourg passengers survived, is there a correlation between these two?
    a. Is it possible that most Pclass 1 passengers embarked from Cherbourg.
    b. Is it possible that most female passengers embarked from Cherbourg.

4.2.1 Observations and Conclusions - Categorical vs Numerical¶

  1. Survived and Age -
    a. Infants in the age group < 5 have survivability rate of 67%.
    b. Passengers in the age group 20 to 45, had the highest death rate of 63%.
    c. Passengers in the age group > 60, also had low survivability rate of 77%.

Age
Age observations suggest that infants were given priority and rescued first.

  1. Survived and individual_fare -
    a. Passengers that paid more have a higher rate of surviving. And this was previously concluded by Pclass and Survived analysis.

individual_fare
About 60% of Passengers that paid over the average fares survived.

Assumptions to check in Multivariate Analysis

a. Is it possible that the passengers that survived in the age group of 20-45 were in Pclass 1?
b. Is there a correlation between Age and family_type. Is it possible that passengers who survived most were from a family with certain number of members.

4.3.1 Conclusions¶
  1. Age and individual_fare - individual_fare was a column that was feature engineered based on fare and family_size. Passengers who paid higher individual_fare survived more. This has been already analyzed. Passengers that paid the most for their fares appear to be in the age group of 30 - 40.
    Age and individual_fare are weakly positively correlated. As Age increased, the individual_fare also increased slightly. Assumption - These could be passengers traveling in Pclass 1.
  2. Age and family_size - Passengers in the family_size of 2-4 appear to survive more. Irrespective of Age, passengers in smaller family_size of 2 had higher survival chance. Passengers that had young children below the age of 15 also had higher survival chance as previously concluded.
    Age and family_size are negatively correlated. As age increases, the family_size decreases.
  3. individual_fare and family_size - As individual_fare increases there is a decrease in family_size. There is a negative correlation between individual_fare and family_size.

5.1 Conclusion¶
  1. There is a strong correlation between the Survived and Sex of passenger.
  2. There is a negative correlation between the Survived and Pclass meaning passengers from lower Pclass (1) survived more than passengers from higher pclass (3). There is a negative correlation between Pclass and Age meaning that Pclass1 passengers were mostly older.
  3. There is a positive correlation between individual_fare and Survived meaning that passengers that paid more also had a better chance of surviving. Also, there is a negative correlation between individual_fare and Pclass meaning the higher the individual_fare, the lower the Pclass(1). Pclass 1 passengers paid more.
  4. There is a negative correlation between family_size and Survived meaning that passengers from smaller family_size survived more.
  5. There is a slightly lower negative correlation between Age and Survived. Younger passengers survived more.
